BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260221T153000Z
DTEND:20260221T163000Z
DTSTAMP:20260221T000000Z
SUMMARY:Storytelling Performance by Donna Washington
DESCRIPTION:Internationally acclaimed Master Storyteller Donna Washington 
 will present “From 1916 to 1966: The Durham Colored Library.” This 
 interactive\, family-friendly performance explores the origins of the 
 Durham Colored Library—beginning inside White Rock Baptist Church—and 
 its growth into a system of branch libraries and a bookmobile serving 
 Durham’s African American community. Through traditional and folktales 
 such as Anansi stories\, Wicked John\, and tales of the Devil\, Ms. 
 Washington will honor the storytelling traditions that inspired\, 
 entertained\, and united generations. The program emphasizes the importance 
 of listening to the stories people tell about themselves in order to truly 
 understand their history.
LOCATION:Main Children's Programming Room\, Main Library (300 N. Roxboro St)
ORGANIZER;CN="Main Library":MAILTO:main@durhamcountylibrary.org
CATEGORIES:Durham
UID:LibCal-14288-16072330
URL:https://durhamcountylibrary.libcal.com/event/16072330
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260221T153000Z
DTEND:20260221T220000Z
DTSTAMP:20260221T000000Z
SUMMARY:Still Telling: A Day of Stories at Durham County Library
DESCRIPTION:This intergenerational\, family-friendly event highlights the 
 Durham Colored Library at Duke (DCL at Duke) program and the enduring power 
 of storytelling to preserve history\, strengthen community\, and foster 
 connection. Rooted in the legacy of Black storytelling that shaped the 
 original Durham Colored Library\, the program also invites participants of 
 all backgrounds to explore how stories—shared on stage\, on the page\, 
 and within the community—create spaces for learning\, belonging\, and 
 shared understanding.\n\n\n	10:30 AM – 11:30 AM (Children’s Programming 
 Room) Storytelling Performance by Donna Washington: Internationally 
 acclaimed Master Storyteller Donna Washington will present “From 1916 to 
 1966: The Durham Colored Library.” This interactive\, family-friendly 
 performance explores the origins of the Durham Colored Library—beginning 
 inside White Rock Baptist Church—and its growth into a system of branch 
 libraries and a bookmobile serving Durham’s African American community. 
 Through traditional and folktales such as Anansi stories\, Wicked John\, 
 and tales of the Devil\, Ms. Washington will honor the storytelling 
 traditions that inspired\, entertained\, and united generations. The 
 program emphasizes the importance of listening to the stories people tell 
 about themselves in order to truly understand their history.\n	 \n	2:00 PM 
 – 3:30 PM (Children’s Programming Room) Author Reading & Book Giveaway 
 with Victoria Scott-Miller: Author Victoria Scott-Miller will read from her 
 book Miss Edmonia’s Class of Wildfires. The session will include audience 
 engagement and interactive elements for children and families. A book 
 giveaway will follow the reading. The anticipated length of this session is 
 one hour to one and a half hours.\n	 \n	2:00 PM – 5:00 PM (Cafe Area) 
 Community Organization Tables During the afternoon\, organizations with a 
 focus on Black storytelling\, arts\, history\, and youth engagement will 
 host tables featuring giveaways\, educational materials\, and opportunities 
 for community connection. Participating organizations will include:\n	\n		 
 Walltown Children’s Theatre\, supporting youth storytelling and 
 performance arts\n		NorthStar Church of the Arts\, integrating faith\, 
 creativity\, and cultural expression\n		Triangle Friends of African 
 American Arts\, advocating for and supporting African American artists and 
 arts organizations\n		Saving Our Stories\, dedicated to preserving African 
 American history in Durham through oral storytelling and the Museum of 
 Durham History’s Story Squad program\n		Pauli Murray Center\, honoring 
 the life and legacy of Pauli Murray through education and community 
 engagement\n		BlackLit Library at Duke Gardens\, promoting Black 
 literature\, literacy\, and access to diverse stories\n	\n	\n
LOCATION:Main Library - Café area - 2nd floor\, Main Library (300 N. Roxboro St)
ORGANIZER;CN="Main Library":MAILTO:main@durhamcountylibrary.org
CATEGORIES:Author Visit, Durham
UID:LibCal-14288-16244191
URL:https://durhamcountylibrary.libcal.com/event/16244191
END:VEVENT
